<script>
//<![CDATA[
      var newTip = new Tip($('bookCover_11912644'), "\n\n  <h2><a class=\"readable bookTitle\" href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11912644-the-address-book?from_choice=false&amp;from_home_module=false\">The Address Book<\/a><\/h2>\n\n      <div>\n        by <a class=\"authorName\" href=\"/author/show/5359.Jane_Clifton?a=9&amp;origin=related_works\">Jane Clifton<\/a>\n      <\/div>\n\n          <div class=\"smallText uitext darkGreyText\">\n            <span class=\"minirating\"><span class=\"stars staticStars notranslate\"><span size=\"12x12\" class=\"staticStar p10\"><\/span><span size=\"12x12\" class=\"staticStar p10\"><\/span><span size=\"12x12\" class=\"staticStar p10\"><\/span><span size=\"12x12\" class=\"staticStar p6\"><\/span><span size=\"12x12\" class=\"staticStar p0\"><\/span><\/span> 3.50 avg rating &mdash; 16 ratings<\/span>            &mdash; published 2011\n          <\/div>\n\n    <div class=\"addBookTipDescription\">\n      \n<span id=\"freeTextContainer940895498154748424\">The Address Book\n\nA funny and moving story about one woman&apos;s search for home ...\n\nReviewed by Heather Stone\n\nAuthor: Jane Clifton\n\nPublisher: Penguin (Viking)\n\nPublished: 30 May 2011\n\nPrice: AU\$32.95\n\nFormat: Paperback 368 pp\n\nCategory: Memoir\n\nJane <\/span>\n  <span id=\"freeText940895498154748424\" style=\"display:none\">The Address Book\n\nA funny and moving story about one woman\'s search for home ...\n\nReviewed by Heather Stone\n\nAuthor: Jane Clifton\n\nPublisher: Penguin (Viking)\n\nPublished: 30 May 2011\n\nPrice: AU\$32.95\n\nFormat: Paperback 368 pp\n\nCategory: Memoir\n\nJane Clifton is raised as an army brat, always on the move, post to post, forever new, fast tracks to adulthood, becomes an adult, war demos, women’s lib, experimental in many facets of her life. Her parents die early, leaving her without answers.\n\nThis is a delightful book. It is in turn a biography, a travel book, a memoir and a history book as seen through the eyes and heart of a very vibrant Melbourne lady, Jane Clifton. Jane is probably known to many of Bonzer’s readers from Australian TV series, particularly in her best known role as the hard prison bookie, Margot Gaffney, in Prisoner. Jane is also an accomplished marriage celebrant, singer, and radio announcer. Her first two books were successful comedic crime novels Half Past Dead and A Hand in the Bush.\n\nThis memoir, insouciant and introspective, begins with Jane describing her child’s brown cardboard suitcase still covered with drab labels from exotic locations. She succumbs to a pull to recreate her life, her parents and her memories by revisiting each of the homes she had lived in until the present point in her life. Her new travels begin with a small budget from cashing up her super, plus a Commonwealth grant to spend some weeks writing in Ireland. From the germination of the idea to the final completion of the book took six years. The journey however, unlike the earlier decades, takes place over only three months, but her writing and our imagination allow us to relive the post war years to the present.\n\nAncient baggage labels bear witness to the sticking power of British Empire glue. On one side, a jaunty pink P&amp;O Orient Lines sticker, embellished with a seahorse, displays the word cabin – indicating that miss j. f. clifton\'s suitcase is not to be stowed in the ship\'s hold for the duration of the voyage. On the other side, a more prosaic faded red label from a previous voyage simply says cabin. My father\'s name and rank, major g. f. h. clifton, are inscribed in the space provided, handwritten in Daddy\'s distinctive, authoritative style, using his Parker pen filled with blue Quink.\n\nIn an inimitable conversational style, she recreates each step, both personally and geographically, using a technique of ‘then’ and ‘now’. She pulls no punches and never descends to euphemisms while describing her own antics, fantasies and phobias, and the intermittent falls from grace of her skittish mother.\n\nThroughout the story, which never palls, the constant underlying theme is: ‘Where do you call home? What makes a home? Is home where the heart is?’ and I imagine this is a question many of us have asked ourselves as inevitable life changes took place. I know I have. I do know I, like Jane, came to Melbourne as an outsider and thus the heady visions of the late \'60s and \'70s had a tremendous and lasting effect on my mind and the course of my future. In many instances, it is obvious that our paths must have crossed in the halcyon era.\n\nIn several instances I found myself laughing aloud, as she has no hesitation in telling a story against herself, particularly when it involves fear of heights, claustrophobia and frequent dire need to race for a toilet at the worst times and places.\n\nI cannot think of anyone who will not enjoy this book. It can be put down, but each time is just as enjoyably picked up again. Even those of us who did not share that era with its unique rites of passage, will love sharing the journey.<\/span>\n  <a data-text-id=\"940895498154748424\" href=\"#\" onclick=\"swapContent(\$(this));; return false;\">...more<\/a>\n\n    <\/div>\n\n      <div class=\'wtrButtonContainer wtrSignedOut\' id=\'23_book_11912644\'>\n<div class=\'wtrUp wtrLeft\'>\n<form action=\"/shelf/add_to_shelf\" accept-charset=\"UTF-8\" method=\"post\"><input name=\"utf8\" type=\"hidden\" value=\"&#x2713;\" /><input type=\"hidden\" name=\"authenticity_token\" value=\"X4ngCnaQnB25JRNdTrDOa+/J57tiAXwAS8Q/T5bb1n9ku4rZ2oNF2PA/cAbiiRtaBZiDENA+yQkiZH/tc05lhg==\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"book_id\" id=\"book_id\" value=\"11912644\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"name\" id=\"name\" value=\"to-read\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"unique_id\" id=\"unique_id\" value=\"23_book_11912644\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"wtr_new\" id=\"wtr_new\" value=\"true\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"from_choice\" id=\"from_choice\" value=\"false\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"from_home_module\" id=\"from_home_module\" value=\"false\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"ref\" id=\"ref\" value=\"\" class=\"wtrLeftUpRef\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"existing_review\" id=\"existing_review\" value=\"false\" class=\"wtrExisting\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"book_origin\" id=\"book_origin\" value=\"related_works\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"page_url\" id=\"page_url\" value=\"/book/show/6330323-day-after-night\" />\n<button class=\'wtrToRead\' type=\'submit\'>\n<span class=\'progressTrigger\'>Want to Read<\/span>\n<span class=\'progressIndicator\'>saving…<\/span>\n<\/button>\n<\/form>\n\n<\/div>\n\n<div class=\'wtrRight wtrUp\'>\n<form class=\"hiddenShelfForm\" action=\"/shelf/add_to_shelf\" accept-charset=\"UTF-8\" method=\"post\"><input name=\"utf8\" type=\"hidden\" value=\"&#x2713;\" /><input type=\"hidden\" name=\"authenticity_token\" value=\"jAbYRydGIkhgzZlj+jP4suE3mVZo1g+ueEyX4vYIbbq3NLKUi1X7jSnX+jhWCi2DC2b9/drpuqcR7NdAE53eQw==\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"unique_id\" id=\"unique_id\" value=\"23_book_11912644\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"book_id\" id=\"book_id\" value=\"11912644\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"a\" id=\"a\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"name\" id=\"name\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"from_choice\" id=\"from_choice\" value=\"false\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"from_home_module\" id=\"from_home_module\" value=\"false\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"book_origin\" id=\"book_origin\" value=\"related_works\" />\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"page_url\" id=\"page_url\" value=\"/book/show/6330323-day-after-night\" />\n<\/form>\n\n<button class=\'wtrShelfButton\'><\/button>\n<\/div>\n\n<div class=\'ratingStars wtrRating\'>\n<div class=\'starsErrorTooltip hidden\'>\nError rating book. Refresh and try again.\n<\/div>\n<div class=\'myRating uitext greyText\'>Rate this book<\/div>\n<div class=\'clearRating uitext\'>Clear rating<\/div>\n<div cla